Secondary analysis of CanCORS multi center cohort study

CHUHAN

10/31/2019

Data cleaning

We select class I & colon Rerun the med/out for colon for second

# import data
cancors_full = read.csv("../data/selected_cancors_data_2019_08_13.csv")[-1]%>%
  janitor::clean_names() %>%
  filter(crc_site==1) # 1219 patients diagnosed with colon cancer only

# regroup income
cancors_full$income[which(cancors_full$income==3)]=2
cancors_full$income[which(cancors_full$income %in% c(4,5))]=3

# regroup education
cancors_full$education[which(cancors_full$education %in% c(-1:12))]=1 # grade/high school
cancors_full$education[which(cancors_full$education %in% c(21:35))]=2 # vocational school/college/university
cancors_full$education[which(cancors_full$education %in% c(41:43))]=3 # graduate/professional school
cancors_full$education[which(cancors_full$education %in% c(-8,-9))]=NA

# regroup qualcare
cancors_full$qualcare[which(cancors_full$qualcare %in% c(2,3))]=2 #very good/good
cancors_full$qualcare[which(cancors_full$qualcare %in% c(4,5))]=3 #fair/poor
cancors_full$qualcare[which(cancors_full$qualcare %in% c(-8,-9))]=NA

# regroup center
cancors_full$center[which(cancors_full$center %in% c(13:15))]=1 # center 13-15
cancors_full$center[which(cancors_full$center == 20)]=2 #center 20
cancors_full$center[which(cancors_full$center == 30)]=3 #center 30
cancors_full$center[which(cancors_full$center ==40)]=4 #center 40
cancors_full$center[which(cancors_full$center ==60)]=6 #center 60
cancors_full$center[which(cancors_full$center ==70)]=7 #center 70

cancors_clean = cancors_full %>% 
  mutate(race=as.factor(race), #'0'='White','1'='Non-White'
         gender=as.factor(as.numeric(gender==1)), #'0'='Female','1'='Male'
         ins=as.factor(as.numeric(ins==1)), #insurance coverage '1'= Yes,'0'= No
         income = as.factor(income), #income level '1'< 20000, '2'< 60000, '3'>=60000
         age = as.factor(age_dx), #age at cancer diagnosis '1'<= 52, '2' > 52,'3'>64
         stage = as.factor(stage), #cancer stage at diagnosis
         region=as.factor(region),#'2','3','4'
         center=as.factor(center), #'1','2','3','4','6','7'
         education=as.factor(education),#highest education received '1'='grade/high school','2'='college/university','3'='graduate/professional school'
         qualcare=as.factor(qualcare), #quality of healthcare '1'='excellent','2'='very good/good','3'=fair/poor
         surgery_status=as.numeric(surgery_status==1), #0-surgery not received, 1-surgery received
         smoking=as.factor(as.numeric(smoking==1)), #smoking habits '1'=Yes,'0'=No
         drinking=as.factor(ifelse(alcohlyr==1,0,1)),#drinking habits '1'=Yes,'0'=No                     
         bmi=703*(weightyearprior/(height_ft*12+height_in)^2), #BMI index for one year prior
         #bmi=as.factor(ifelse(bmi<0,NA,ifelse(bmi<18.5,1,ifelse(bmi<25,2,ifelse(bmi<30,3,4))))), #'1'=underweight, '2'=normal, '3'=overweight, '4'=obese
         comorbidity=as.factor(ifelse(diabetes==1|stroke==1,1,0)), #indicator of co-morbidity '1'=Yes,'0'=No
         health_status=ifelse(health_status_ayearago %in% c(-8,-9), NA, health_status_ayearago)/10,#health status for one year prior 
         rel_days_rca_surg=ifelse(is.na(rel_time_surgery) | is.na(rel_days_rca_bsln), surv,rel_time_surgery + rel_days_rca_bsln),
         #20 patients in total did not receive any kind of trt(surgery,chemo,radiation), we replace missing values in Time to treatment with survival time
         rel_days_rca_rd=rel_time_radio+rel_days_rca_bsln,
         rel_days_rca_chm = rel_time_chemo + rel_days_rca_bsln
         ) %>%
  filter(dxothcan!=1,
         bmi>0)%>%
  dplyr::select(race,gender,age,income,education,stage,smoking,drinking,comorbidity,health_status,bmi,surgery_status,ins,rel_days_rca_surg,rel_days_rca_rd,rel_days_rca_chm,surv,cens,region,center)

# identify the first treatment received for each patient
trt_cate=which(names(cancors_clean) %in% c("rel_days_rca_surg","rel_days_rca_chm","rel_days_rca_rd"))
t=unlist(apply(cancors_clean[trt_cate],1,which.min),use.names=FALSE) # to determine first trt by minimzing relative time to each trt
cancors_clean$fst_trt=as.factor(colnames(cancors_clean[trt_cate])[t])
t_time=unlist(apply(cancors_clean[trt_cate],1,min,na.rm=T), use.names=FALSE)
cancors_clean$time_fst_trt=t_time
table(cancors_clean$fst_trt)

Visulization of censored survival tiem

ggplot(data=cancors_impute,aes(x=surv))+geom_histogram()+geom_vline(xintercept =365*5,col="red",linetype=2)+facet_wrap(~cens)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

min(cancors_impute[which(cancors_impute$cens==0),]$surv) 
## [1] 1929
  • The minimum of censored survival value(cens=0) is 1929 -> great than 5 years.Therefore, we will further use five-year survival indicator(ind) as the outcome.

Distribution of time to treatment by cancer stages

For patients diagnosed at different cancer stages, we noticed a bimodal distribution of time to surgery(in log scale) across all the stages. The trough values between the two peaks range from 2.8 to 3.0, which probably indicate the existence of other factors that are well-related to patients treatment waiting time. Especially, we further change the mediator from time to surgery to time to first treatment.The similar plot was shown in figureXX-no significant difference for patients diagnosed at colon stage1-stage3, but this value has a relatively large increase for patients diagnosed at colon stage4. We thus assume patients with late stage colon cancer receive more chemo/radiation therapy than early stage patients.

Latent class analysis-identify the class membership for each patient by time to surgery

##   1   2 
## 478 733
  • 733 Patients are classified as early trt group, 478 patients are classified as late trt group

Mediator Modeling

Based on the result from Random Forest analysis, we would investigate the potential inteaction with class membership in mediator model. For outcome model, we would go with the cancer stage at diagnosis.

KM Curves for time to surgery

# Only stratify by center
ggsurvplot(survfit(Surv(time_surg, surgery_status) ~ center, data = med.rf),censor.shape="|", censor.size = 3,pval = TRUE, conf.int=FALSE,legend.title="center",ggtheme = theme_bw(),ylab="Waiting Probability", xlab="Time to surgery")

ggsurvplot(survfit(Surv(time_surg, surgery_status) ~ center, data = med.rf),censor.shape="|", censor.size = 3,facet.by="stage",pval = TRUE, conf.int=FALSE,legend.title="center",ggtheme = theme_bw(),ylab="Waiting Probability", xlab="Time to surgery")

AFT analysis

Draw a histogram to show the distribution of center by stage and plot time to surgery by center

# Create text labels
percentage = cancors_select %>% 
  group_by(center,stage) %>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>%
  mutate(percent = count/sum(count),
         ypos=sum(count)-cumsum(count)+0.5*count) 
  
center_stage <- ggplot(cancors_select,aes(center,group=stage)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill=stage,y=(..count..)), width = 0.5) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=65, vjust=0.6)) +
  #geom_text(aes(y=(..count..),label=(..count..)),stat = "count")
  geom_text(data=percentage,aes(label=round(percent,2),y=ypos), colour="black", size=2.5)+theme_bw()+labs(title = "Patient distribution across center by stage" )
center_stage

The patinent distibution across stage is relatively proportioned in center1. From the KM curves, we also see a significant decrease in Time-to-surgery for patients from center1. Therefore, we chose center1 as the reference group to build the AFT model.

cancors_select$center <- relevel( cancors_select$center, ref="1" )

Part1 - Only adjust for stage

# factor stage

In order to check whether the assumed distribution of survival times fits the observed data sufficiently well, we can use the residuals of the model. However, because the residuals are calculated based on the observed event times, they will also be censored. Hence, to investigate whether they follow a particular distribution, we will need to employ a graphical procedure accounting for censoring. One way to achieve this is by using the Kaplan-Meier estimator of the residuals.

Diagnostic Plot

fitted_values <- med.fit.all$linear.predictors
resids <- (log(med.fit.all$y[, 1]) - fitted_values) / med.fit.all$scale

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
resKM <- survfit(Surv(resids, surgery_status) ~ 1, data = cancors_select)
plot(resKM, mark.time = FALSE, xlab = "AFT Residuals", ylab = "Survival Probability")
xx <- seq(min(resids), max(resids), length.out = 35)
yy <- exp(- exp(xx))
lines(xx, yy, col = "red", lwd = 2)
legend("bottomleft", c("KM estimate", "95% CI KM estimate", 
    "Survival function of Extreme Value distribution"), 
    lty = c(1,2,1), col = c(1,1,2), bty = "n")

  • From the result, patients from center7 take siginificant longer time to receive appropriate treatment compared to patients from center1. But this geographic effect is further modified by the cancer stage mildly - late stage diagnosis would mitigate the effect of center on patientss waiting time to treatment.

  • For patients diagnosed at stage1 colon cancer, time to treatment in center7 is increased by a factor of \(e^{0.4743-0.1039}=1.45\) compared to center1 , while this acceleration factor decreas to \(e^{0.4743-4*0.1039}=1.06\) for stage4 colon cancer.

PH analysis

PH assumption

we check the proportional hazards assumption by appropriately transforming the Kaplan-Meier estimate in the log-log scale. In this scale we would expect to see parallel lines.

med.fit.center.km=survfit(Surv(time_surg,surgery_status)~center,data=med.rf)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(med.fit.center.km, fun = function (s) -log(-log(s)), xlab = "Years", ylab = "-log(- log(Survival))", col = 1:7)

plot(med.fit.center.km, xlab = "Years", ylab = "Survival", col = 1:7) 
legend("topright", levels(med.rf$center), lty = 1, col = 1:7, bty = "n")

The plot in the right panel of the gure is the classical Kaplan-Meier estimator (survival probabilitieson the y-axis). The plot in the left panel has log[ log{S(t)}] on the y-axis - transformation of the survival function S(t).

In builing the mediator model, we would like to test for the eect of stage. Hence, the model under the null hypothesis is the one that does not contain stage. we use the likelihood ratio test by comparing the models under the null and alternative hypothesis. This is done using the anova() function.

anova(med.fit.stage.cox, med.fit.all.cox)
## Analysis of Deviance Table
##  Cox model: response is  Surv(time_surg, surgery_status)
##  Model 1: ~ center * stage_n
##  Model 2: ~ center * stage_n + race + gender + age + income + education + smoking + drinking + comorbidity + health_status + bmi + ins
##    loglik  Chisq Df P(>|Chi|)
## 1 -7188.1                    
## 2 -7178.7 18.648 14    0.1789

Hence, we could proceed with the null model. From the modeling results:
* The treatment rate for patients from center7 is only \(e^{-0.8523+0.1570}=0.50\) of the one in center1 regarding stage1 colon cancer diagnosis.
* But for patients diagnosed with stage4 colon cancer, this disparity in treatment rate for center7 versus center1 decrease a little bit - the rate ratio is estimated as \(e^{-0.8523+0.1570*4}=0.80\).

Hence, we will go with the non-linear assumption and NOT consider the time-to-surgery/stage interaction and time-to-surgery/center interaction.

Mediation Analysis

We here compare the survival outcome by cancer stages for patients in center7 against center1.

The results suggest the estimated ACMEs are statistically dierent from zero for patients diagnosed at stage 1&2. When diagnosed with stage 1 colon cancer, the 5-year survival rate for patients in center7 are 10.32%, 1-exp(-0.10897), lower compared to patients in center7. To further segment the effect of this geographic difference, we can see that 23.3% of this effect works through increasing waiting time for surgery in center7, which in turn made patients less likely to reach 5-year survival. Here, as the outcome is binary, all estimated eects are expressed as the decrease/increase in probability that the subject has 5-year survival since the diagnosis of colon cancer.
